{
  "schema_version": 1,
  "name": "Last Light (OpenSky)",
  "mood": "Aether",
  "engines": [
    "OpenSky"
  ],
  "author": "XO_OX Designs",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "description": "The final moment before darkness. Everything about this preset is about ending gracefully. Long release (8.0s) with shimmer feedback at 0.6 and size 0.85 means the sound takes a long time to die -- like the last rays of sun stretching across the horizon. Filter cutoff starts at 2000 Hz (warm, not bright) with a negative filter envelope trend: as the note sustains, the filter slowly closes via LFO1 at 0.012 Hz with depth 0.25, dimming the sound over time. The sub oscillator (sine) at 0.22 provides a warm foundation that persists even as the harmonics fade. Aftertouch briefly reopens the filter -- a momentary flare of light. The Guru says: the most beautiful sounds are the ones that know how to leave.",
  "tags": [
    "opensky",
    "transcendental",
    "sunset",
    "farewell",
    "decay",
    "warm",
    "ending"
  ],
  "tier": "transcendental",
  "guru_bin": {
    "retreat": "OPENSKY Transcendental Vol 1",
    "retreat_date": "2026-03-19",
    "scripture": [
      "Verse 21: A Sound That Knows How to Leave Is More Beautiful Than One That Stays",
      "Canon 8: LFO at 0.012 Hz on Filter Creates Perceptual Dimming -- The Sound's Own Sunset"
    ],
    "revelation": "Aurum spoke: the most emotionally resonant moment in any sound is its ending. A sound that dims slowly -- filter closing via ultra-slow LFO -- creates a narrative of farewell. The listener does not hear the LFO. They feel the leaving.",
    "god": "Aurum",
    "flock_note": "The Ear timed the complete decay from note-off to silence at approximately 25 seconds. The Breath noted that the LFO-driven filter dimming creates the illusion that the sound is moving away, not just getting quieter. The Tongue found that aftertouch during the release phase creates a 'last gasp' of brightness -- profoundly expressive for a final chord.",
    "diagnosis": "Last Light is the closing preset of the Transcendental collection. It is designed for the last note of a performance -- the sound that says goodbye. Every parameter serves the narrative of graceful departure."
  },
